## Differential Geometry

It dawns on me I will need to formalize differential geometry before I
can formalize Lie groups (which I almost certainly need when formalizing
finite groups of Lie type).

There have been, I believe, three Mizar articles written about
**topological** manifolds. None have been written about differential
manifolds. The convention used in the topological manifolds follows the
Bourbaki convention for defining a chart on $M$ as a pair $U\subset M$ and
$\varphi\colon U\subset M\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$ injective.

My first inclination is to define a chart, then an atlas, an finally a
maximal atlas; we have a manifold be a structure consisting of a carrier
and an atlas. But I don't think this is necessary, per se. There may be
a "hack" around this, thanks to the way `the` encodes the global choice
operator and the uniqueness of the maximal atlas; this would allow us to
do this like write `the maximal atlas of [manifold]` _as if_ `maximal atlas`
were a field in a structure. This requires a new mode `Atlas of M`, and
a new attribute `maximal` for `Atlas of M`.

The basic outline would be:
- Define `Chart of M`
- Define `are_compatible` for two charts of M
  - Prove `are_compatible` is an equivalence relation (reflexive,
    transitive, symmetric)
- Define `Atlas of M`
- Define `are_equivalent` for two atlases of M
- Define `Subatlas of A` for an atlas A of M. (Perhaps not needed?)
- Define an attribute `maximal` for an Atlas of M
- Prove any two maximal atlases of M are equivalent

OH WAIT! For some manifolds, there are multiple inequivalent maximal
atlases. This approach **cannot work.**

We **must** define a `ManifoldStr` as consisting of a carrier and a
maximal atlas over the carrier. We can then define topological
properties on a `ManifoldStr`, which permits us to define a `Manifold`
as a second-countable paracompact Hausdorff non-empty `ManifoldStr`.

### Differentiable Structure is not unique

I must reiterate again, given some set of points which has at least one
maximal atlas, there may be multiple maximal atlases.

For example, the 7-sphere has multiple distinct smooth structures (this
is the so-called [exotic sphere](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exotic_sphere)).
Or $\mathbb{R}^{4}$ has uncountably many distinct smooth structures
([exotic $\mathbb{R}^{4}$](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exotic_R4)).

